roles/websphere_jvm_restart/tasks/snow_update.yml
---
- name: Validate ServiceNow endpoint settings
  assert:
    that:
      - snow_instance_url | length > 0
      - snow_update_path | length > 0
    fail_msg: "snow_instance_url and snow_update_path must be set."

- name: Build headers
  set_fact:
    snow_headers: >-
      {{
        {
          'Accept': 'application/json',
          'Content-Type': 'application/json'
        }
        | combine(
            (snow_bearer_token | length > 0)
            | ternary({'Authorization': 'Bearer ' ~ snow_bearer_token}, {})
          )
      }}

- name: POST update to ServiceNow
  uri:
    url: "{{ snow_instance_url }}{{ snow_update_path }}"
    method: POST
    headers: "{{ snow_headers }}"
    body_format: json
    body: "{{ snow_body_info }}"
    validate_certs: "{{ snow_validate_certs }}"
    force_basic_auth: "{{ (snow_user | length > 0) and (snow_password | length > 0) }}"
    user: "{{ snow_user | default(omit) }}"
    password: "{{ snow_password | default(omit) }}"
    status_code: [200, 201, 202, 204]
  no_log: true
4) What exactly made it faster (and why)
A) serverStatus.sh -all reduced drastically

Old: per JVM you might do pre + post → 2 * num_jvms calls
New: per profile you do pre once + post once → 2 * num_profiles calls
If you have 1 profile with 10 JVMs, you cut from 20 calls → 2 calls.

B) Install root check only once per host

Old: if PID missing, you might stat 4 roots per JVM.
New: you stat once, cache cached_install_root, reuse it for all JVMs.

C) Banner writes reduced

Old: per JVM banner updates
New: banner is set once per profile batch (and only for the owner used). Cleanup once at host end.

D) Still safe stop/restart

You still get:

stop async
PID disappearance polling
kill -9 if needed
verify PID gone before starting
5) Example showing env behavior with this optimized flow

Payload:

jvm_restart:
  ritm_number: RITM9999
  envs:
    dev:
      hosts:
        devapp1:
          AppSrv01: [server1, server2]
    prod:
      hosts:
        prodapp1:
          AppSrvP01: [server1]

Build inventory creates groups:

wsjvm_restart_targets_dev: devapp1
wsjvm_restart_targets_prod: prodapp1

Execute play (hosts: all) runs only on:

devapp1 (in dev group)
prodapp1 (in prod group)

And each host processes:

profile batches (serverStatus per profile once pre/post)

If you want the failed_hosts format to be exactly ["host:profile:jvm"] (without env), I can switch aggregation to use host_profile_jvm (one-line change), but since you now use envs, keeping env in the string is usually better for review.
